# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ron-barassi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] The **1940 VFL season** was the 44th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 27 April until 28 September, and comprised an 18-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Melbourne Football Club for the fourth time and second time consecutively, after it defeated Richmond by 39 points in the 1940 VFL Grand Final.
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] In 1940, the VFL competition consisted of twelve teams of 18 on-the-field players each, plus one substitute player, known as the **19th man**.
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] A player could be substituted for any reason; however, once substituted, a player could not return to the field of play under any circumstances.
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] Teams played each other in a home-and-away season of 18 rounds; matches 12 to 18 were the "home-and-way reverse" of matches 1 to 7.
[src:ron-barassi/1940-vfl-season] Once the 18 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1940 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:ron-barassi/1953-vfl-season] The **1953 VFL season** was the 57th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:ron-barassi/1953-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 18 April until 26 September, and comprised an 18-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:ron-barassi/1953-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Collingwood Football Club for the twelfth time, after it defeated Geelong by twelve points in the 1953 VFL Grand Final.
[src:ron-barassi/1953-vfl-season] In 1953, the VFL competition consisted of twelve teams of 18 on-the-field players each, plus two substitute players, known as the **19th man** and the **20th man**.
[src:ron-barassi/1953-vfl-season] Once the 18 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1953 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-grand-final] The **1954 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Footscray Football Club and Melbourne Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on 25 September 1954.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-grand-final] It was the 57th annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League (VFL), staged to determine the premiers for the 1954 VFL season.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 80,897 spectators, was won by Footscray by 51 points, marking that club's first VFL premiership.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-grand-final] Footscray had won nine premierships in the Victorian Football Association (VFA) before entering the VFL in 1925.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-grand-final] Footscray led by 29 points at quarter-time and were comfortably in front for the rest of the game.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-grand-final] Jack Collins kicked 7 goals for the match and John Kerr had 32 disposals.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-season] The **1954 VFL season** was the 58th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 17 April until 25 September, and comprised an 18-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Footscray Football Club for the first time, after it defeated Melbourne by 51 points in the 1954 VFL Grand Final.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-season] In 1954, the VFL competition consisted of twelve teams of 18 on-the-field players each, plus two substitute players, known as the **19th man** and the **20th man**.
[src:ron-barassi/1954-vfl-season] Once the 18 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1954 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The **1955 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Melbourne Football Club and Collingwood Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on 17 September 1955.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] It was the 58th annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1955 VFL season.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 88,053 spectators, was won by Melbourne by 28 points, marking that club's seventh premiership victory.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] A scene from the game is captured in Jamie Cooper's painting *The Game That Made Australia*, commissioned by the AFL in 2008 to celebrate the 150th anniversary of the sport.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Melbourne's qualification for its second consecutive VFL Grand final appearance capped one of the most remarkable turnarounds in VFL/AFL history; only two seasons prior, the club had finished second-last on the ladder.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] In very wet and muddy conditions, Melbourne advanced straight to the Grand final in a torrid 11-point Second Semi-final victory against Collingwood.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] After being on top of the ladder going into Round 15 of the 1954 season, Collingwood suffered a dramatic form slump, losing all its remaining home-and-away games to end in seventh position.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Despite some early season setbacks in 1955, the Magpies were in the top four by Round 6 and stayed there for the remainder of the season, vying with Geelong for second and third position.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Both teams finished the home-and-away season with 14 wins and four losses, but Collingwood's superior percentage helped it claim second place.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] After their loss to Melbourne in the above-mentioned Semi-final, the Magpies rallied to beat Geelong in an entertaining Preliminary final by 12 points and gain a second crack at Melbourne.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The two teams met only once in the home-and-away season, in Round 11 at Victoria Park, when Collingwood prevailed by 3 points.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The umpiring panel for the match, comprising one field umpire, two boundary umpires and two goal umpires is given below.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The MCG surface was still drying out on Grand final day, but the whole game was played in glorious sunshine.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Melbourne's intent to physically dominate was made clear early in the game when captain Noel McMahen fiercely bumped Collingwood champion Bob Rose with a legitimate hip-and-shoulder charge a split second after Rose had kicked the ball into attack.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] From the resulting downfield free kick, Murray Weideman scored the first goal of the game.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] After a slow start, Melbourne's physical vigour eventually wore down a determined Collingwood team.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] In the annals of VFL/AFL history, the 1955 Grand Final is mostly remembered for one of the most sickening on-field incidents during a match.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] In the final stages of the game, the Demons had pulled away to a 13-point lead when Collingwood wingman Des Healey won the ball and dashed down the wing.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Norm Smith had just replaced Geoff Case, who was suffering from cramps, with 20th man Frank "Bluey" Adams, who sprinted onto the ground and into the path of Healey.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Adams had barely been on the ground ten seconds.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Concerned Collingwood officials were further angered when a miscommunication resulted in a two-hour wait for an ambulance.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Healey was eventually transported to St Vincent's Hospital with concussion, shock, a nose badly broken in five places and a fractured skull – this last injury was not identified until years later when Healey was forced to have X-rays following a car accident.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] As Collingwood supporters jeered and threw bottles, rubbish and fruit at Adams as he was carried from the field, Smith feared a riot.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Adams remained unconscious for 40 minutes, during which time Melbourne had won the game.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] When he eventually came to, he gibbered, "Don't take me off, Norm, my leg's all right!" before being taken by ambulance to the Alfred Hospital, where he was diagnosed with concussion.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Melbourne's victory marked the first of six VFL premierships for Norm Smith as coach; he had been full-forward in Melbourne's previous premiership triumph in 1948.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The Demons would become the dominant team of the decade, participating in six further VFL Grand finals and winning five during that period.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] The decade also marked a golden era in the club's rivalry with Collingwood; 1955 would be the first of five times the two teams faced each other in VFL Grand finals, with Melbourne winning four of those encounters.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-grand-final] Even as of 2023, eight of the top ten match attendance figures between Melbourne and Collingwood were from between 1955 and 1964, including the record VFL/AFL crowd figure for a home-and-away fixture – 99,256 in 1958.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-season] The **1955 VFL season** was the 59th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 16 April until 17 September, and comprised an 18-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Melbourne Football Club for the seventh time, after it defeated Collingwood by 28 points in the 1955 VFL Grand Final.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-season] In 1955, the VFL competition consisted of twelve teams of 18 on-the-field players each, plus two substitute players, known as the **19th man** and the **20th man**.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-season] Teams played each other in a home-and-away season of 18 rounds; matches 12 to 18 were the "home-and-away reverse" of matches 1 to 7.
[src:ron-barassi/1955-vfl-season] Once the 18 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1955 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] The **All-Australian team** is an all-star team of Australian rules footballers, selected by a panel at the end of each Australian Football League (AFL) season.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] It represents a complete team, including an interchange bench, of the best-performed players during the season, traditionally led by that season's premiership coach.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] The concept of an All-Australian team originated as recognition of performance in interstate football.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] They were named after each Australian National Football Carnival, beginning with the 1953 Adelaide Carnival.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] In the 1980s All-Australian teams were named annually to recognise the best performers in State of Origin series.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Following the AFL's expansion to a national competition with teams in multiple states, the first AFL All-Australian team was named in 1991.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Despite the name's implication, the All-Australian team is usually ceremonial in modern times.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Though the AFL played an All-Star match in 2020, it was the first in 12 years, and the difference in skill level between the All-Australian team and the nearest international competitor is currently too large for any contest to be competitive.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Despite this, some of these players have represented Australia in AFL Academy junior teams up to the age of 18, as more than two-thirds of all AFL Academy representatives have gone on to play at senior AFL level.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] From 1998 to 2004, the Australian international rules team was mainly composed of All-Australians, and from 2005 to 2013 the team for the annual International Rules Series was selected according to the quite different requirements of International rules football.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] This change was reverted ahead of the 2014 series, with any player who had been selected at least once in *any* All-Australian team being eligible for selection.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] The earliest concept considered to be a precursor to the All-Australian team was an annual team selected by *Sporting Life* magazine between 1947 and 1955.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] A panel of sportswriters at the magazine selected a full team of eighteen from all ANFC-affiliated competitions.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] For a time, AFL historians considered these teams to be official All-Australian teams, but no longer recognises them as such.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] The first official All-Australian team was selected in 1953, immediately after the Australian Football Carnival, which was held in Adelaide on that occasion.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Based solely upon performances at the carnival, the All-Australian team was selected by representatives of the various state teams.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] This tradition continued at all subsequent interstate carnivals until 1988.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] In 1991, following the VFL's conversion to a national competition and its renaming as the Australian Football League (AFL), an annual All-Australian team based on performances during the AFL premiership season was introduced.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Since 1999, the All-Australian coach is the coach of the premiership-winning side that year.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Prior to 2007, only the final selections in the All-Australian team were announced.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Since 2007, the All-Australian selection committee has nominated the 40 leading players of the year in their playing positions at the conclusion of the home and away season, before announcing the final 22 at a later date during the All-Australian Presentation Dinner.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] The 2023 All-Australian selection panel consists of chairperson Gillon McLachlan, Kevin Bartlett, Eddie Betts, Jude Bolton, Nathan Buckley, Kane Cornes, Andrew Dillon, Glen Jakovich, Laura Kane, Cameron Ling, and Matthew Pavlich.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] In addition to the senior All-Australian team, each year an All-Australian line-up is announced based on the AFL National Under 18 Championships and the AFL National Under 16 Championships.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] The following lists are for senior teams only.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Members of the All-Australian team are awarded a team blazer, reminiscent of the formal wear traditionally worn by travelling members of national sports teams.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p01] Blazers have become synonymous with the identity of the honour.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p03] The AFL website recognises players who were named in the VFL/AFL Team of the Year from 1982 to 1990 as having All-Australian status.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p03] This was a team picked by Victorian selectors.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p03] Teams were named every season from 1982 to 1990, except 1985.
[src:ron-barassi/1956-all-australian-team-p03] These teams were once considered to be equivalent to All-Australian selection, but are no longer recognised as such.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] When Barassi was five years old, his father, Melbourne Football Club player Ron Barassi Sr., died in action at Tobruk during World War II.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was determined to follow in his father's footsteps at Melbourne, and heavy lobbying by the club to recruit him resulted in the introduction of the father–son rule, still in use by the AFL today.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi subsequently lived with Norm Smith, Melbourne's then-coach and a former teammate of his father.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Under Smith's mentorship, Barassi pioneered the ruck-rover position and appeared in six premiership-winning sides, two of which he captained.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1964, in what has been called "the most audacious signing in league history", Barassi left Melbourne for a lucrative contract at Carlton.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi retired from professional football in 1971, but he was lured back two years later to coach North Melbourne.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1981, after leading the club to its first two premierships, he returned to an ailing Melbourne, where he initiated the "Irish experiment": the recruitment of Gaelic footballers into Australian rules.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] His stint at Melbourne, followed by another at the Sydney Swans in 1993–95, proved vital in rebuilding those clubs as viable members of the competition.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi's coaching career was both successful and regarded by many as revolutionary, and his clean record and passion for the game earned him a place as a celebrity and popular culture figure in Australia.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] A prominent early campaigner for a national club-level competition, he is the namesake of the Barassi Line, which describes the regional split between football codes in Australia.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He was named a Member of the Order of Australia in 1978, and in 1996 was selected in the AFL's Team of the Century as a ruck-rover.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Following his death, Barassi was honoured with a state funeral.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The only child of Ron Barassi, Sr., Barassi was born in the central Victorian town of Castlemaine on 27 February 1936.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The following year, his father moved to Melbourne to play VFL football with the Melbourne Football Club.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] A pugnacious rover, Barassi's father was a reserve in the Demons' 1940 premiership team before leaving to serve with the army in North Africa, where he died in the Siege of Tobruk.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The young Barassi spent his early years in Guildford, Victoria.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He was educated at Castlemaine Tech and then at Preston and Footscray techs in Melbourne.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was a third-generation Italian Australian whose Swiss Italian ancestors migrated to Victoria during the gold rushes of the 1850s and 1860s.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] They settled areas such as Guildford, Castlemaine and Daylesford.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi unintentionally changed the game before he even took the field.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] After his father's death at Tobruk in 1941, a group of players and officials at the Melbourne Football Club pledged to support his widow, Elza, and her young son.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] As a teenager, Barassi was determined to follow in his father's footsteps at the Demons, but the zoning system of the day required him to play for either Collingwood or Carlton.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] To ensure he played with the Demons, Melbourne went to the VFL and successfully lobbied for the creation of a father–son rule to allow clubs preferential recruiting access to the sons of players who have made a major past contribution to the team (50-game minimum at launch).
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] When the time came for Barassi to be signed, Melbourne picked him from Preston Scouts in 1952 and he became only the second player signed under the new rule (after Harvey Dunn Jr).
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] This rule, with some modifications and adapted to the drafting system created in 1986, endures to the present day in the AFL.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The club had gone to great lengths to recruit the young Barassi, and coach Norm Smith took him under his wing after his mother moved to Tasmania.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Smith offered the 16-year-old use of his backyard bungalow.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Looking back on the experience, Barassi believed that living with the man who was voted as the coach of the AFL's Team of the Century had a profound impact on his development.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Melbourne Football Club was the dominant team of the 1950s.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Under the coaching of Norm Smith, Barassi developed quickly.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi's first game was against Footscray in 1953 in which he was shirtfronted by Footscray's Charlie Sutton.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Initially unsure as to Barassi's best position, Smith played him as a second ruckman in 1954 despite his lack of size for the position.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi played more as a second rover, and the term "ruck-rover" entered the football lexicon.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Within a few years, most teams imitated this structure, which ultimately paved the way for a new style of quicker on-ball play.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi soon proved himself as an influential footballer, and he was quickly handed leadership responsibilities.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1957, he was appointed vice-captain, and he was made captain three years later.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] After losing the 1954 Grand Final to a more experienced Footscray football team by 51 points, the Demons dominated the VFL by winning three successive flags in 1955, 1956, and 1957, with the team at the time hailed as the best to ever play the game.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The image of Barassi breaking a tackle in the 1957 Grand Final is captured in Jamie Cooper's painting *The Game That Made Australia*, commissioned by the AFL in 2008 to celebrate the 150th anniversary of the sport.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] A resurgent Carlton gave him a dilemma in 1964.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] New president George Harris was desperate to have Barassi at Princes Park, and he was willing to offer a lucrative deal for the time – a three-year contract of A£9,000 (equivalent to $151,320 in 2023) plus bonuses — if Barassi would cross to Carlton as captain-coach.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Carlton offered Barassi a chance to test his skills as coach with a professional wage which would help with his children's education.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] On his decision to leave Melbourne, Barassi said that "Inevitably with many decisions in life there will be a downside.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] It is regrettable but you have to get on with things", he said.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] "You have to ensure, as much as possible, that the decision you've made turns out right.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi's coaching at Carlton brought them from their lowest-ever VFL finish (at the time) to premiers only four years later.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Drawing from his own experience under Norm Smith, Barassi forced his squad to become more disciplined and committed to the club—and their career.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He preached and played a tough brand of football, and asked his charges to play a selfless, team-oriented style.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1968, he guided Carlton to its first premiership in 21 years.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] After the 1971 season, Barassi left the Blues to focus on his business career.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Despite not having played football since 1969, he signed to play with Port Melbourne in the Victorian Football Association in 1972, but he played only four games before suffering a hamstring injury and retiring.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] With administrators Allen Aylett and Ron Joseph, he recruited a new batch of stars for North Melbourne.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Proven champions were recruited from clubs throughout the country, including Malcolm Blight, Barry Cable, John Rantall, Barry Davis and Doug Wade.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] North Melbourne won the wooden spoon in 1972, finishing last.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] However, in 1974, in just Barassi's second year of coaching the club, North Melbourne were to come runner-up in the 1974 grand final.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Whereas Barassi had implemented a tough training regime in 1974, he modified this approach for the 1975 finals when he introduced lighter training sessions to keep his squad mentally-focused and not overtrained and exhausted.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] His strategy worked and they won the 1975 premiership.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] North Melbourne went on to win another premiership in 1977, but they nearly squandered the flag as they gave up a late lead against Collingwood to create the second-ever drawn VFL grand final before coming back a week later to win the flag.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In the drawn grand final, Barassi made major positional changes, including placing North Melbourne Team of the Century full-back and captain David Dench into the forward line, which sparked North Melbourne's comeback to get back in front until Ross Dunne kicked a late goal to draw the game.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Within a week, Barassi had picked his side up from this disappointing setback to lead North to a memorable triumph.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1981, Barassi returned to Melbourne to assist long-term under-19 coach Ray 'Slug' Jordon.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The under-19s made three straight grand finals and won premierships in 1981 and 1983.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi laid some foundations for what would become a revitalised Melbourne side.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] "In the five years we were there I think we raised the level of the club quite substantially.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Melbourne reached the preliminary final two years after we left, and the grand final the year after that.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi started the "Irish experiment" at Melbourne, which started recruiting Gaelic footballers from Ireland and converting them to Australian rules footballers.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He recruited the most famous of all, the 1991 Brownlow Medallist, Jim Stynes.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1993, Barassi returned to coaching for the Sydney Swans.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] This was seen as a coup for the AFL given Barassi's media skills and profile.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In his three seasons in Sydney, he raised the profile of Australian rules football and the Sydney Swans in the rugby league–dominated city.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] On 4 March 1957, Barassi married Nancy Kellett, whom he had met at work four years earlier.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] They settled in the eastern suburbs of Melbourne, at Heathmont, and had three children between 1960 and 1964.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The couple separated in 1975 and Barassi married Cherryl Copeland (born in St Kilda, Melbourne) in 1981.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] They were married until his death in 2023.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Both Ron and Cherryl were active supporters of the voluntary assisted dying movement.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] During his coaching career at North Melbourne he survived a car crash, which caused life-threatening injuries and resulted in the loss of his spleen.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] His passenger, former St Kilda player and Brownlow medallist Neil Roberts, was also hurt.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi used a motorised buggy and a wheelchair for a short time.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Despite this setback, he attended training nights at Arden Street and could be seen directing players with assistants.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi's first trip overseas occurred in 1961.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1967, in New York City during the Australian Football World Tour, Barassi was involved in a fight in which detective Brendan Tumelty broke Barassi's nose and both were sent to the same hospital.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi moved to the suburb of St Kilda in the late 1970s and lived there until his death.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was a passionate chess player, playing many games of classical chess in the late 1970s over the phone with Brent Crosswell—a player whom Barassi was actively coaching—often for more than four hours at a time and lasting 50–60 moves per game.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In a newspaper article, Crosswell humorously described how Barassi would psychologically break Crosswell down in over-the-board games by neglecting to bring him food or drinks and that “he would never provide chairs bearing any logical relationship to the table on which the chess set was placed”.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] For many years, Barassi owned the Mountain View Hotel at 70 Bridge Road in Richmond.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] For his 70th birthday he did a trek of the Kokoda Trail in Papua New Guinea.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] On 28 February 2008, Barassi launched and signed his book *Barassi*, focusing on his personal life and scrapbook memoirs.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] On New Year's Eve 2008, Barassi was assaulted when he went to the aid of a young woman in St Kilda.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi, dining with friends, saw a woman punched to the ground around 12.30 am.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In January 2012, Barassi suffered a bike accident, cracking three ribs.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In September that year, aged 76, he went on to crew a yacht at Hamilton Island Yacht Racing Week with his friend John Bertrand.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] For his brave defence of the woman on New Year's Eve 2008, Barassi received a bravery award in 2012 and a commendation for brave conduct in 2013.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] On 16 September 2023, Barassi died following complications from a fall.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] After retiring from coaching, Barassi remained a prominent Australian rules football celebrity and a figure of popular culture.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 1996, he became an inaugural inductee in the Australian Football Hall of Fame, one of few former greats to be bestowed the honour of the "Legend" category.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He is also one of only three Australian rules footballers in the Sport Australia Hall of Fame, alongside Leigh Matthews and Ted Whitten.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was involved in grassroots football development and was an advocate for the development of the game internationally, particularly in South Africa.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Reflecting this, Barassi lent his name to the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was a supporter of Australia becoming a republic.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was one of the last runners in the Queen's Baton Relay for the 2006 Commonwealth Games, being held in Melbourne, Australia, from 15 to 26 March.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] His section of the relay, run on 15 March, involved taking the baton from a series of pontoons in the middle of the Yarra River onto shore.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] It was handed to him by David Neitz, captain of the Melbourne Football Club (the team with which Barassi was long associated).
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] This was accomplished by having Barassi walk on a pontoon that was submerged just beneath the surface of the water, giving the impression that Barassi was "walking on water".
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi is the namesake of the Barassi Line, a concept originated by scholar Ian Turner to describe the geographical divide in Australia between Australian rules football and the two rugby codes.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The line is imagined to intersect the border towns of Corowa and Wahgunyah, where, in 2014, Barassi attended the unveiling of a plaque commemorating the Barassi Line.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Robert Helpmann's 1964 ballet *The Display* includes a lengthy football sequence for which Helpmann recruited Barassi to coach the male dancers in Australian rules.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi wrote the introduction to Philip Hodgins' 1990 poetry collection *A Kick of the Footy*.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The frontman of satirical Melbourne band TISM went under the pseudonym Ron Hitler-Barassi.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi disliked the reference, saying "My father was killed by Hitler's men in Tobruk so you can imagine my displeasure." Artist Lewis Miller won the 2000 "Sporting Archibald" for his portrait of Barassi, which was acquired by the National Portrait Gallery in Canberra.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi has appeared in the Specky Magee books.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 2015, Barassi collaborated with singer-songwriter Tex Perkins on the song "One Minute's Silence", a tribute to the diggers who died at Gallipoli.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He was mentioned several times in episodes of the television show *Kingswood Country*.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He was one of the first footballers to have his own football clinic on television and during the 1960s.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] He also launched his popular "Ron Barassi" footy boots.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In September 2003, a bronze statue depicting Barassi kicking based on a famous photograph was unveiled at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In late 2006, he became a Sport Australia Hall of Fame member.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The best player in the Under-17 International Rules Series is awarded the Ron Barassi Medal.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] Barassi was the subject of a series 2 episode of *Who Do You Think You Are?*.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] In 2012, Australian playwright Tee O'Neill adapted Barassi's life into a theatrical performance.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] The play script was published by Currency Press.
[src:ron-barassi/ron-barassi] A bronze bust of Barassi was unveiled in his hometown of Guildford to celebrate his 80th birthday on 27 February 2016 .
